				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Siemens and Mitsubishi Counteroffer for Alstom Is Less Than G.E.&#8217;s Bid</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By David Jolly and Jack Ewing			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-06-16T16:52:10+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">June 16, 2014 12:52 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">June 16, 2014 12:52 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/17/business/ALSTOM/ALSTOM-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/17/business/ALSTOM/ALSTOM-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/06/17/business/ALSTOM/ALSTOM-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002944283" width="592" height="395" alt="An Alstom gas turbine. Siemens is interested in Alstomâs valuable gas-turbine business."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">An Alstom gas turbine. Siemens is interested in Alstomâs valuable gas-turbine business.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> John Rawlston/Chattanooga Times Free Press, via Associated Press</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/16/siemens-and-mitsubishi-heavy-make-9-5-billion-counteroffer-for-alstom-assets/" data-title="Siemens and Mitsubishi Counteroffer for Alstom Is Less Than G.E.&#8217;s Bid" data-description="Siemens and Mitsubishi Heavy Industries formally presented a counteroffer for Alstom, but their combined bid was less than what General Electric was offering.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="t17h12m" class="update">Updated, 5:12 p.m. | </span>PARIS &#8212; Siemens and Mitsubishi Heavy Industries <a href="//www.siemens.com/investor/pool/en/investor_relations/financial_publications/ad_hoc_announcements/ad-hoc-announcement-16-06-2014.pdf">formally presented a counteroffer</a> for Alstom on Monday in an attempt to assuage French fears about losing one of its most important companies, even as their combined bid was less than what General Electric had proposed.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/06/15/siemens-and-mitsubishi-heavy-industries-nearing-an-offer-for-alstom/" title="Siemens and Mitsubishi Poised to Bid for Alstom">joint bid is a complex offer</a>. As part of the bid, Siemens said it would pay 3.9 billion euros, or $5.3 billion, in cash for Alstomâs business making turbines for the gas generation industry. Siemens also promised to preserve jobs for three years and locate the European headquarters of its gas business in France.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//www.siemens.com/investor/pool/en/investor_relations/financial_publications/ad_hoc_announcements/AXX20140646_ENG.pdf">Mitsubishi said</a> it would pay â¬3.1 billion for minority stakes in the Alstom units that make steam generators and equipment for nuclear power plants, as well as units that supply the hydroelectric power. Alstom would retain a majority in the units and management, leaving much of the company in French hands, while acquiring money for investment.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mitsubishi said it would acquire 40 percent of Alstomâs steam turbine and nuclear power business, 20 percent of Alstomâs business supplying equipment for electricity grids, and 20 percent of the French companyâs hydropower business.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In addition, Mitsubishi Heavy said it would offer to buy as much as 10 percent in Alstom by purchasing shares now held by Bouygues. Alstom would retain its French stock market listing, Mitsubishi said.</p>
		<div class="w190 right">
		<img src="//markets.on.nytimes.com/research/tools/builder/api.asp" width="190" height="250" alt=""/>		</div>
		
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/04/27/france-warns-alstom-on-possible-g-e-alliance/" title=" France Defers G.E. Plan to Buy Energy Business (April 27, 2014)">battle to acquire Alstom has become largely a political contest</a>, with the bidders aiming to appeal to the French government more than to shareholders. G.E. has offered $13.5 billion for Alstomâs energy assets.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After acquiring the Alstom gas business, Siemens said, it would then consider combining its rail business to create a âEuropean champion.â Alstom and Siemens both make high-speed passenger trains.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âAlstom would remain an independent energy and transport player with a strong brand,â Joe Kaeser, the chief executive of Siemens, said in a statement.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The new bid is a threat to the ambitions of Jeffrey R. Immelt, G.E.&#8217;s chairman and chief executive. G.E., based in Fairfield, Conn., wants the business to bolster its own substantial energy operations, and like Siemens, it is particularly interested in Alstomâs valuable gas-turbine business.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Deirdre Latour, a G.E. spokeswoman, said the company remained confident that its offer was âgood for Alstom, for France and for G.E.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe have made progress in our discussions with the French government, including alliances in energy and transport,â she said. âThis would ensure that Alstom remains a vibrant player in both industries.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The counteroffer came as something of an anticlimax, falling well short of the cash offered by General Electric and surprisingly short of the kind of detail that Alstom&#8217;s board would need to compare the offers. General Electric had extended its offer until next Monday at the French governmentâs request.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Siemens and Mitsubishi Heavy executives insisted in a background briefing with skeptical journalists in Paris that their offer was much better than G.E.&#8217;s.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThis offer is significantly stronger in its valuation of the assets,â the senior Siemens executive said, adding: âThis is not about money, it&#8217;s about making a stronger Alstom. It preserves Alstom.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The executives spoke on the condition of anonymity because they did not want to preempt the French government&#8217;s own announcement, expected on Tuesday.  President FranÃ§ois Hollande was to meet with the heads of Siemens and Mitsubishi at the Elysee Palace on Tuesday morning to discuss the new offer.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The senior Mitsubushi executive described the proposal as âa binding offer,â but he acknowledged that his company had not yet conducted due diligence on Alstom. Nor has Mitsubishi yet spoken with Bouygues about its possible stake purchase, he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">He also said that Mitsubishi would be âvery happyâ to have the government as a shareholder, if it should decide to take a stake.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One analyst said the joint offer appeared to be a serious contender.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;Before this point, it looked like it was G.E.&#8217;s deal to lose,&#8221; Steven Winoker, an analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein in New York, said. &#8220;Now there&#8217;s a  viable alternative on the table from the other parties.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âMr. Winoker said that while the offers were different enough to make the comparison difficult,  the new bid &#8220;looks like about a 25 percent premium to the G.E. offer.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Nonetheless, he said, the Alstom board might still prefer G.E.&#8217;s offer, as it kept the gas- and steam-turbine businesses together. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">G.E. has said it doesn&#8217;t want to get into a bidding war, he noted, but it does have room to increase its offer.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">G.E. has the backing of Alstomâs chairman and chief executive, Patrick Kron, but the American giantâs interest met with strong initial resistance from Mr. Hollande&#8217;s struggling government, which learned about the negotiations from news reports. French officials do not want to see a prized industrial asset, including parts of the strategic nuclear sector, falling under foreign control, and have since decreed that it has the right to a final say on national security grounds.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Alstom said in a statement that executives of Siemens and Mitsubishi had made their pitch on Monday to Mr. Kron and other members of the board, and that the proposal would be reviewed &#8220;and submitted to the board of directors of Alstom in the coming days.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Alstomâs energy business specializes in a number of areas besides gas turbines, including hydropower and offshore wind technology, but its profit margins are declining and it lacks the scale to compete effectively at the global level. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After news of the G.E. negotiations became public, the French economy minister, Arnaud Montebourg, enlisted Siemens in the hopes of finding a âEuropeanâ solution to Alstomâs problems, or at least of encouraging G.E. to make an offer more acceptable to the government.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Montebourg&#8217;s office did not immediately respond to a request for comment. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Immelt has done his best to assuage the governmentâs concerns, promising to keep crucial parts of Alstomâs operations in France and to safeguard jobs, even creating 1,000 new positions. After initially giving G.E. a cold shoulder, the French government now maintains that it is âneutralâ on the rival offers.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">G.E.&#8217;s offer would split off only the energy assets, which last year contributed about two-thirds of the French companyâs â¬20.3 billion of total revenue; the rest of Alstom would remain as a stand-alone transportation business, a domain in which it excels, with high-speed trains, urban- and freight-rail systems and railroad infrastructure.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mitsubishi Heavy, under its chief executive, Shunichi Miyanaga, would quickly gain scale for its Mitsubishi Hitachi Power Systems joint venture. Indeed, there have been reports suggesting that Hitachi, its venture partner, would help to finance the Alstom bid. Hitachi declined to comment.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>David Jolly reported from Paris and Jack Ewing from Frankfurt.</em></p>
<div id="addendums" class="addendums"><div class="story-addendum theme-correction"><strong>Correction: June 16, 2014</strong> <br>An earlier version of this article misspelled the given name of the chief executive of  Mitsubishi Heavy Industries. He is Shunichi Miyanaga, not Shunishi.</div></div><footer class="story-footer">
